items.author: Reuters
items.content:
1. South Korea's parliament impeached acting President Han Duck-soo on Friday over a short-lived martial law, plunging the country deeper into political chaos, as the Constitutional Court said it would swiftly trial suspended President Yoon Suk Yeol.

2. Russian air defences downed an Azerbaijan Airlines plane that crashed in Kazakhstan, killing 38 people, four sources with knowledge of the preliminary findings of Azerbaijan's investigation into the disaster told Reuters on Thursday.

3. The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said on Thursday its analysis of samples from the first severe case of bird flu in the country last week showed mutations not seen in samples from an infected backyard flock on the patient's property.

4. Blurry images of two seemingly new Chinese military aircraft with stealthy characteristics appeared online on Friday, with defence experts saying they were clearly advanced designs, but there was not enough detail for definitive conclusions.

5. Described as a "reluctant king" in his first stint as prime minister, the soft-spoken Manmohan Singh, who died on Thursday at the age of 92, was arguably one of India's most successful leaders.

items.title: Russian air defenses downed Azerbaijan Airlines flight, sources say
items.author: Reuters
items.content:
Russian air defenses downed an Azerbaijan Airlines plane that crashed in Kazakhstan, killing 38 people, four sources with knowledge of the preliminary findings of Azerbaijan's investigation into the disaster told Reuters.
 
Flight J2-8243 crashed in a ball of fire near the city of Aktau in Kazakhstan after diverting from an area of southern Russia where Moscow has repeatedly used air-defense systems against Ukrainian drone strikes.
 
The Embraer passenger jet had flown from Azerbaijan's capital Baku en route to Grozny, before veering off hundreds of miles across the Caspian Sea and crashing on the opposite shore.
 
One of the Azerbaijani sources familiar with the investigation told Reuters that preliminary results showed the plane was struck by a Russian Pantsir-S air-defense system. Its communications were paralyzed by electronic warfare systems on the approach into Grozny, the source said.
